Kotun Sojoji A Najeriya Ta Kama Babban Soja Da Laifin Satar Fiye Da Biliyan Daya

Kotun Sojin Najeriya ta musamman da ke zamanta a Abuja ta ce ta samu Maj-Gen Umaru Muhammed da laifin satar $1.476m.

Muhammed shi ne tsohon shugaban kungiyar Nigerian Army Properties Limited, NAPL.

Shugaban kotun, Maj.-Gen. James Myam, ya ce a ranar Larabar da ta gabata, a yayin da ake shari‚Äôar, wanda ake tuhumar ya ki amsa laifinsa, inda ya gabatar da shaidu biyu.

Ya ce kotun ta samu wanda ake kara da laifin satar dalar Amurka miliyan 1.04 tsakanin 7 ga Mayu, 2019, zuwa 24 ga watan Yuni, 2021, a lokacin da yake aiki a matsayin GMD na NAPL.

Shugaban kotun ya kara da cewa, an samu wadanda ake tuhumar da laifin umurtar wani Manjo Usman da ya ajiye kudaden a asusun banki.

Mista Myam, ya ce ba a sami Mista Muhammed da laifi ba a shari‚Äôa ta 7, wanda ke da iyaka da hada baki da laifuka na jabun takarda tare da wani Yusuf Abdulahi.

Sai dai an same shi da laifin yin karya dangane da tuhume-tuhume 8 da 9 na satar dala 430,800, in ji shugaban kotun.

Kotun ta kuma samu Janar din da laifin hada baki wajen hada takardu, da kuma sayar da kadarorin kamfanin a lokacin da ya daina aiki a NAPL kan Naira miliyan 200.

Ta kuma same shi da laifin rashin gaskiya da karbar Naira miliyan 74 daga asusun kamfanin a ranar 22 ga Agusta, 2019.

A wani labarin kumaDalilin Da Yasa Muka Amince Da Balarabe Duk Da Cewar Ya Fadi A Lokacin Tantancewa-Majalisa

A kan tuhume-tuhume 14, 15, 16, da 18, wadanda ke da alaka da karkatar da kudade da sauran laifuka, kotun ta ce wadanda ake tuhumar ba za su iya bayarda lissafin Naira biliyan 2.5 na kamfanin ba.

A shari‚Äôa 17, inda ake tuhumar Janar din da fitar da Naira miliyan 750 daga asusun kamfanin, kotun ta ce masu gabatar da kara sun gaza tabbatar da zargin nasu ba tare da wata shakka ba.

South Africans of faith must acknowledge that Israeli policies towards Palestinians are a carbon copy of the apartheid-era policies in South Africa or risk becoming complicit in the subjugation of Palestinians, the leader of the Anglican Church of Southern Africa (ACSA) has said.

In a statement released on 29 September, Thabo Makgoba, the Anglican Archbishop of Cape Town, said that the Church had recognised Israel as an apartheid state.

‚ÄúAs people of faith who are distressed by the pain of the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza - and who long for security and a just peace for both Palestine and Israel - we can no longer ignore the realities on the ground,‚Äù Makgoba said.

‚ÄúOur hearts ache for our Christian brothers and sisters in Palestine, whose numbers include Anglicans but are rapidly declining. People of all faiths in South Africa have both a deep understanding of what it is to live under oppression,‚Äù he continued, before comparing Israel to South Africa under apartheid rule.

‚ÄúWhen black South Africans who have lived under apartheid visit Israel, the parallels to apartheid are impossible to ignore. If we stand by and keep quiet, we will be complicit in the continuing oppression of the Palestinians,‚Äù Makgoba added.

While the South African Zionist Organisation lashed out at the resolution, with its chairperson calling the resolution "appalling" and "antisemitic" - other civil society groups like the Palestine Solidarity Committee and South African BDS Coalition, warmly welcomed the decision.

The Anglican Church said its stance was not an attack on Jewish people, "but to the policies of Israelis' governments, which are becoming ever more extreme".

"We salute the Anglican Church for not only calling out Israeli apartheid but also taking action,‚Äù South Africa's BDS Coalition said.

"The Anglican Church of Southern Africa is standing on the right side of history, fully supporting the Palestinian struggle for equality, human rights and justice," the coalition added.

The UN's special rapporteurs and several human rights organisations, such as Amnesty International, have concluded that Israel practises apartheid

Hala Alqadi, seorang atlet karate Palestin yang berusia 22 tahun, telah mencipta sejarah dengan memperoleh pingat gangsa di Sukan Asia Hangzhou. 
 
Hala Alqadi merangkul pingat gangsa kumite 68kg wanita selepas menewaskan lawannya dari China Taipei, Chao Jou 6-3. Pingat ini merupakan pingat Palestin yang pertama dalam Sukan Asia Hangzhou dan pingat Sukan Asia pertama sejak 2002. 
 
"Ia adalah kemenangan yang bersejarah. Saya sangat gembira kerana akhirnya dapat menaikkan bendera Palestin dalam salah satu pertandingan antarabangsa." 
 
"Palestin berhak untuk hidup dengan aman dan mencapai semua impian mereka dan jauh daripada konflik," katanya. 
 
"Kami boleh mencipta masa depan berdasarkan keupayaan, bakat, dan pembangunan insan kami. Kami hanya mahu diberi peluang untuk hidup dengan selamat dan membuktikan kewujudan kami sebagai rakyat Palestin." 
 
Alqadi memberitahu hasratnya untuk meneruskan karier atlet karate di pentas antarabangsa dan kini sedang bersiap sedia untuk sertai Kejohanan Dunia di Hungary pada Oktober nanti. 
 
"Hala Alqadi serta semua rakyat Palestin, berhak mendapat kemenangan bersejarah ini, terutama ketika kita semua mencari detik-detik kebahagiaan," jelas Jayousi. 
 
Alqadi dan Jayousi memuji Sukan Asia yang diadakan di China. Masyarakat di sana meraikan kemenangan Alqadi dengan meriah. 
 
"Tahniah di atas pencapaian yang hebat. Tahniah kepada Hala dan Palestin atas pingat ini yang amat disayangi oleh kita semua," kata Bahjat Tantish, individu yang berpangkalan di Gaza, dalam akaun Facebooknya. 
 
"Kemenangan adalah untuk Palestin dan rakyat Palestin di mana-mana."

#onthisdayinhistory The Yom Kippur War began with an Egyptian and Syrian attack on land held by Israel from the Six Day War on October 6, 1973. In 1967, Israel launched a preemptive strike against Egypt in the Six Day War and subsequently occupied the Sinai Peninsula, the entirety of Palestine, and the Golan Heights. The capture of the Sinai Peninsula was a massive blunder for Egypt as they had to shut down the Suez Canal in its entirety. The war ended with both sides agreeing to a ceasefire. 

Both Egyptian and Syrian military planners saw a window of opportunity to attack Israel due to the ongoing Jewish holiday of Yom Kippur. Egypt in particular hoped to capture the eastern bank of the Suez Canal in order to leverage Israel into giving back the occupied Sinai Peninsula. As Egyptian forces advanced into the Sinai Peninsula, Syrian forces attacked the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. After three days of heavy fighting, Israel halted the Egyptian advance and pushed Syria back to the pre-war ceasefire line. Israel then launched a four-day counteroffensive into Syria and managed to start shelling the Syrian capital of Damascus. Egyptian forces attempted a breakout, but failed and Israeli forces then pushed into Egypt. An October 22 United Nations brokered ceasefire fell apart, with each side blaming the other. As the Israelis pushed more and more towards the Egyptian capital of Cairo, tensions between the US (who supported Israel) and the Soviet Union (who supported Egypt) rose as well. A second ceasefire was imposed on October 25, which was far more successful and ended the war. 

The Yom Kippur War had some long-reaching impacts. Despite facing yet another humiliating defeat from Israel, the Arab powers did feel some sense of vindication with their early successes. Israel also accepted the fact that there may come a time when their military is not as dominant as previously believed. Both of these changes led to the beginning of an Israeli-Palestinian peace process and the 1978 Camp David Accords, where Israel agreed to give the Sinai Peninsula back to Egypt in exchange for Egypt recognizing Israel as a legitimate state. #yomkippurwar #israel #egypt #syria

‚ÄúAs people of faith who are distressed by the pain of the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza - and who long for security and a just peace for both Palestine and Israel - we can no longer ignore the realities on the ground,‚Äù Makgoba said.

‚ÄúOur hearts ache for our Christian brothers and sisters in Palestine, whose numbers include Anglicans but are rapidly declining. People of all faiths in South Africa have both a deep understanding of what it is to live under oppression,‚Äù he continued, before comparing Israel to South Africa under apartheid rule.

‚ÄúWhen black South Africans who have lived under apartheid visit Israel, the parallels to apartheid are impossible to ignore. If we stand by and keep quiet, we will be complicit in the continuing oppression of the Palestinians,‚Äù Makgoba added.

While the South African Zionist Organisation lashed out at the resolution, with its chairperson calling the resolution "appalling" and "antisemitic" - other civil society groups like the Palestine Solidarity Committee and South African BDS Coalition, warmly welcomed the decision.

The Anglican Church said its stance was not an attack on Jewish people, "but to the policies of Israelis' governments, which are becoming ever more extreme".

"We salute the Anglican Church for not only calling out Israeli apartheid but also taking action,‚Äù South Africa's BDS Coalition said.

"The Anglican Church of Southern Africa is standing on the right side of history, fully supporting the Palestinian struggle for equality, human rights and justice," the coalition added.

The UN's special rapporteurs and several human rights organisations, such as Amnesty International, have concluded that Israel practises apartheid
